{"award_age":60.0,"bio_image":"full\/183f04c2849122a2be85bbd337d1f60ff80fc17f.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1946-08-07T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/7\/72\/John_Mather_%28cropped%29.jpg\/220px-John_Mather_%28cropped%29.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_C._Mather","mini_bio":"<p><b>John Cromwell Mather<\/b> (born August 7, 1946, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Roanoke,_Virginia\" title=\"Roanoke, Virginia\">Roanoke<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Virginia\" title=\"Virginia\">Virginia<\/a>) is an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Astrophysics\" title=\"Astrophysics\">astrophysicist<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cosmology\" title=\"Cosmology\">cosmologist<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> laureate for his work on the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cosmic_Background_Explorer\" title=\"Cosmic Background Explorer\">Cosmic Background Explorer Satellite (COBE)<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Smoot\" title=\"George Smoot\">George Smoot<\/a>.<\/p><p>This work helped cement the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Big-bang\" title=\"Big-bang\" class=\"mw-redirect\">big-bang<\/a> theory of the universe. According to the Nobel Prize committee, \"the COBE-project can also be regarded as the starting point for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cosmology\" title=\"Cosmology\">cosmology<\/a> as a precision science.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-nobel_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_C._Mather#cite_note-nobel-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Mather is a senior astrophysicist at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/NASA\" title=\"NASA\">U.S. space agency's (NASA)<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Goddard_Space_Flight_Center\" title=\"Goddard Space Flight Center\">Goddard Space Flight Center (GSFC)<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Maryland\" title=\"Maryland\">Maryland<\/a> and adjunct professor of physics at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Maryland,_College_Park\" title=\"University of Maryland, College Park\">University of Maryland, College Park<\/a>. In 2007, Mather was listed among <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Time_(magazine)\" title=\"Time (magazine)\"><i>Time<\/i> magazine's<\/a> 100 Most Influential People in The World. In October, 2012, he was listed again by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Time_(magazine)\" title=\"Time (magazine)\"><i>Time<\/i> magazine<\/a> in a special issue on New Space Discoveries as one of 25 most influential people in space.<\/p><p>Mather is also the project scientist for the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Webb_Space_Telescope\" title=\"James Webb Space Telescope\">James Webb Space Telescope (JWST)<\/a>, a space telescope to be launched to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lagrange_Point\" title=\"Lagrange Point\" class=\"mw-redirect\">L2<\/a> no earlier than 2018.<\/p><p>In 2014, Mather delivered a major address on the Webb Space Telescope at the second <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Starmus_Festival\" title=\"Starmus Festival\">Starmus Festival<\/a> in the Canary Islands.<\/p>","name":"John C. Mather","place_of_birth":"Roanoke ,  Virginia ,  United States","place_of_death":null,"text":"John C. Mather , Physics, 2006","year":2006.0}